SUMMARY:Alligator River Wildlife Paddle (Manns Harbor)
DESCRIPTION:Join NCWF’s Wildlife Habitat Stewards of Northeastern NC Chapter and Coastal Kayak for a guided paddle through Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge on Sunday\, April19\, from 10 a.m. to 12 p.m. As you glide through the calm refuge waters\, keep an eye out for alligators\, river otters\, and a wide variety of birds and other species enjoying their natural habitats. \nEstablished in 1984\, the refuge protects the rare pocosin wetlands\, unique ecosystems built on deep peat soils and covered with low\, shrubby vegetation. The area also includes swamp forest and is bordered by rich marshland. This vast protected landscape supports thriving populations of black bears and wintering waterfowl\, and it’s one of the only places in the world where you might spot endangered Red Wolves in the wild. \nEnjoy this unforgettable two-hour adventure for just $45 per person\, which includes experienced guides\, a kayak\, and all necessary gear. Both single and double kayaks are available. \n**After you register here\, you’ll receive a confirmation email with a link for payment and reservation of your kayak with Coastal Kayak.**\n\n 
URL:https://ncwf.org/event/alligator-river-wildlife-paddle-manns-harbor/
CATEGORIES:Featured
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://ncwf.org/wp-content/uploads/alligatorriverpaddle.jpg
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Wildlife Federation
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260423T080000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260423T160000
DTSTAMP:20260403T221536
CREATED:20260317T181513Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260317T181513Z
UID:10001543-1776931200-1776960000@ncwf.org
SUMMARY:Cerulean Warbler & Avian Diversity Study
DESCRIPTION:Join North Carolina Wildlife Federation\, National Parks Conservation Association\, the Center for Biological Diversity\, Defenders of Wildlife\, MountainTrue\, and the N.C. Wildlife Resources Commission with support from the U.S. Forest Service to help with a cerulean warbler and avian diversity survey project focused on the last remaining patches of old-growth forests and maturing second-growth forests within the Craggie Mountains – Pisgah National Forest where presence of ceruleans and many other avian species is largely unknown. \nOur goal is to fill area-specific knowledge gaps to provide best available information for future decision making in forest management and conservation efforts. To achieve this goal\, we are using acoustic recording units (ARUs). The units are mounted to trees within suitable habitat and automatically record songs at dawn and dusk everyday for weeks at a time. \nNorth Carolina Wildlife Federation is looking for volunteers to join us in the field. The Craggie Mountains are known for their rugged terrain\, steep slopes and mature forests. Volunteers will be expected to hike 5 + miles off trail in sometimes physically challenging conditions to reach target sites and install ARUs. Volunteers will start with a team lead and training will be provided. \nNCWF will be leading volunteers in the field on – \nThursday\, 4/23\nThursday\, 5/7\nThursday\, 5/21\nThursday\, 6/4\nThursday\, 6/18\nThursday\, 7/2\nThursday\, 7/16\nThursday\, 7/30\nThursday\, 8/13\nThursday\, 8/27 \nWe’ll start by 9AM and spend 6 to 7 hours in the field. Carpooling from the Asheville area will be available. Please email Luke Bennett luke@ncwf.org if you are interested in volunteering and we’ll be in touch with more information – what to bring\, where to meet\, etc. See you out there!
URL:https://ncwf.org/event/cerulean-warbler-avian-diversity-study-7/
CATEGORIES:Featured
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Wildlife Federation
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260423T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260423T200000
DTSTAMP:20260403T221536
CREATED:20260209T154652Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260209T154653Z
UID:10001480-1776967200-1776974400@ncwf.org
SUMMARY:Inaugural Smoky Mountains Wilderness Watch Earth Day Social (Balsam)
DESCRIPTION:Are you passionate about wildlife? Do you want to make a difference in your corner of the world? \nAs the newest developing chapter of the North Carolina Wildlife Federation\, the Smoky Mountains Wilderness Watch advocates for wildlife conservation\, habitat protection\, and responsible land stewardship across the Western North Carolina counties of Haywood\, Jackson\, and Swain. \nJoin us at the Balsam Mountain Inn (Jackson County) between Sylva and Waynesville to learn more about the chapter and discover different ways to get involved. A cash bar will be available. This event is free of charge and all are welcome!  \nREGISTER HERE
URL:https://ncwf.org/event/earth-day-social-balsam/
CATEGORIES:Featured
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://ncwf.org/wp-content/uploads/SMWWBalsam-1-1.jpg
END:VEVENT
